## Summary

- Moves user timer management (setTimeout/setInterval) from Rust's `BTreeSet` to a JavaScript-side implementation matching Node.js's timer architecture: linked lists bucketed by duration, binary min-heap priority queue, and a single native wake mechanism (`UserTimer`).
- Rust now provides only a simple single-deadline `UserTimer` ("wake me at time T") via `op_timer_schedule`/`op_timer_now`, while JS manages all timer data structures and scheduling via `processTimers(now)`.
- System timers (e.g. `AbortSignal.timeout`) remain on the existing Rust `WebTimers` path.
- Fixed ID collision between web timer IDs and system timer IDs by having `AbortSignal` use `core.refTimer`/`core.unrefTimer` directly.

This is Phase 1 of aligning Deno's timer architecture with Node.js to ensure timers fire in the correct event loop phase.

### Key files
- `libs/core/02_timers.js` — **new** JS timer infrastructure (linked lists, priority queue, `processTimers`)
- `libs/core/web_timeout.rs` — `UserTimer` struct (single-deadline native wake mechanism)
- `libs/core/ops_builtin_v8.rs` — `op_timer_schedule`, `op_timer_now` ops
- `libs/core/runtime/jsruntime.rs` — `dispatch_user_timers()`, event loop integration
- `ext/web/02_timers.js` — rewritten to use `core.createTimer()` instead of `op_timer_queue`

